Prasa has been identified as one of six entities which contributed to half of the country's irregular expenditure. CAPE TOWN The Passenger Rail Agency of South Africa (Prasa) s R14 billion in irregular expenditure, incurred in the previous financial year, has come under the spotlight in Parliament.Prasa executives are briefing Parliament's Standing Committee on Public Accounts on irregular, fruitless and wasteful expenditure identified in the Auditor-General's recent report.Prasa has been identified by the Auditor-General as one of six entities which contributed to half of the country's irregular expenditure over the 2015/16 financial year.Democratic Alliance (DA) Member of Parliament (MP) David Ross says it s concerning that Prasa was the worst performing out of more than 400 state-owned companies. The generally accepted accounting practices lacked in Prasa [and] transparency lacked. Board chairperson Popo Molefe has acknowledged the situation is bad but has argued problems have been brought to light because they are being investigated. We re able to uncover irregular items, which in the past the Auditor-General had not been able to pick up. These things had not been exposed. We have exposed them. (Edited by Tamsin Wort)